0 @69579143@ NOTE
1 CONT I can’t read the information but I ran it through AI.All AI results not always 100% correct.
1 CONT Of course! This is a fascinating page from a Status Animarum (Book of Souls). These books were kept by parish priests to track the families in their parish. The script is old German Kurrent, which can be challenging to read.
1 CONT Here are the translations and explanations for the notes you asked about.
1 CONT Note for Kravagna Albin
1 CONT The note you mentioned isn't under the first name but in the "Mores" (Conduct/Remarks) column next to Kravagna Albin.
1 CONT • German Transcription: obiit in Zivilspital zu Laybach 1832, 31 May
1 CONT • English Translation: Died in the Civil Hospital in Laibach (Ljubljana) on May 31, 1832.
1 CONT Laybach is the historical German name for Ljubljana, the capital of Slovenia.
1 CONT Note for Raker Anton
1 CONT This is the longer note in the "Mores" column next to Raker Anton (born 1803). This comment is a character assessment by the priest.
1 CONT • German Transcription: brav sich führend und das Brod bey jenem Meister erwerbend, welcher ihn als Knaben aufgenommen
1 CONT • English Translation: "Conducting himself well and earning his living with the master who took him in as a boy."
1 CONT This note provides a positive character reference, indicating that Anton was of good conduct and gainfully employed by the same person who had taken him in when he was young.
1 CONT Understanding Mervar Elisabetha & Family Structure
1 CONT The document lays out the family structure, including several illegitimate children, which was not uncommon. Here's a breakdown to help with your search for Mervar Elisabetha:
1 CONT 1. The Core Family (House No. 6):
1 CONT • Kravagna Albin: Head of household.
1 CONT • Raker Gertraud: Listed as uxor (wife).
1 CONT • Jacob (b. 1822): Their son. The note next to his name, legitimatus, means he was legitimized, likely by the marriage of his parents.
1 CONT 2. Gertraud's Illegitimate Children:
1 CONT The children listed below the main family—Anton, Agnes, Ursula, and Chatarina—all have the mother's surname, Raker (or it is implied). This indicates they were born out of wedlock before her marriage to Albin Kravagna.
1 CONT • Raker Anton (b. 1803): This is the man with the long note about his good character.
1 CONT • † Agnes (b. 1805): The note obüt 26 August 830 means she died on August 26, 1830.
1 CONT • † Ursula (b. 1811): The note obiit means she died. No date is given here.
1 CONT • † Chatarina (b. 1814): The note obiit 12 August 830 zu Puchenberg Nro 97 means she died on August 12, 1830, in Puchenberg, house No. 97. ("Puchenberg" is the German name for a location in Slovenia, possibly Puconci).
1 CONT 3. Anton Raker's Family:
1 CONT Mervar Elisabetha is listed directly under Raker Anton. This pairing suggests they formed their own family unit. The two children listed below them are likely theirs:
1 CONT • Anton f. (filius, meaning son), b. 1832
1 CONT • Johann, b. 1835
1 CONT To find more records for Mervar Elisabetha, I would suggest looking for a marriage record for her and Anton Raker. This marriage likely took place sometime before the birth of their first son in 1832, so searching in the parish records for the years 1830-1832 would be a great place to start. That record should provide more details about her parents and place of origin.
